# Iliotibial Band (ITB)

> The **iliotibial band** (IT band / iliotibial tract) is a thick band of fascia lata running down the lateral thigh from the [[Iliac Crest]] to Gerdy's tubercle on the lateral [[Tibia]]. It receives the insertions of [[Gluteus Maximus]] and [[Tensor Fasciae Latae]].

## 🔗 Key Connections
- **Origin** — [[Iliac Crest]] (tubercle); [[Gluteus Maximus]] + [[Tensor Fasciae Latae]] insert into it
- **Insertion** — Gerdy's tubercle (anterolateral [[Tibia]])
- **Crosses** — Lateral femoral condyle at ~30° of knee flexion

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **IT band syndrome (ITBS)** — Most common running overuse injury; friction of ITB over lateral femoral condyle → lateral knee pain at 30° flexion; treated with stretching, activity modification
- **Segond fracture** — Avulsion of lateral tibial rim by ITB (+ anterior capsule); associated with ACL tear

